 relationship to Charlotte von Hardenberg, features prominently in the correspondence, yet neither his family in Lausanne nor his friends in Paris and elsewhere are neglected. The correspondence also describes in detail important events of these years in which the Napoleonic Era reached its high point.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn French.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 4aConstant, Benjamin. 4aEmpire. 4aFrankreich (Literatur, Briefwechsel). 4aPolitische Theorie. 4aReligion. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / European / General.2bisacsh  aConstant, Benjamin.  aEmpire.  aFrance (Literature, Correspondence).  aPolitical Theory.  aReligion.1 aDelbouille, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDelbouille, Paul.1 aRickard, Peter.1 aTocke, Adrianne.1 aTooke, Adrienne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWood, Dennis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWood, Dennis.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Literary and Cultural Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110637854oZDB-23-GLC0 cprintz978348450456140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311097395240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110973952423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110973952/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-GLCc2000d2014